When migrating the current code to:
EdgeIteratorState edge = graph.edge(3, 5).setDistance(200).set(accessEnc, true, true).set(speedEnc, 60, 60);
there are two problems: if we throw an explicit error we cannot easily refactor the current usages as speedEnc is often not for two directions. Except we set the backward value in a silent manner which I did in 418454a#diff-305b1d577b70e729c3845b447da93e1bc9668716a1c4b2e0928987b8623380b0R174, but I do not like it that much for our Java API.
And the code will be longer:
EdgeIteratorState edge = graph.edge(3, 5).setDistance(200).set(encoder.getAccessEnc(), true, true).set(encoder.getSpeedEnc(), 60, 60);
So for now I would prefer to keep it (simpler?) like:
EdgeIteratorState edge = GHUtilities.setSpeed(60, 60, encoder, graph.edge(3, 5).setDistance(200));
This code then uses the implicit setReverse:
if (avgSpeedEnc.isStoreTwoDirections()) edge.setReverse(avgSpeedEnc, bwdSpeed);
which I find acceptable for the utility function and it has also the advantage that no access encoded value is mentioned and a speed of 0 would indicate that the direction is blocked.
